\f0\fs24 \cf2 <!$Scr_Ps::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f2\fs32 Whenever a potential difference exists between two points in a circuit, whether created by a battery, a generator, or some other voltage source, it will drive electrons from the more negative point towards the more positively point.  This is called 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\b\fs32 electron flow
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\fs32 , or 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\b\fs32 electron current
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\fs32 .\
Sadly, electron current is not technically 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\b\fs32 current
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\fs32 ! This is because, in 1752, before the nature of electric charge and electrons was fully understood,  Benjamin Franklin 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f4\i\fs32 defined
\f0\i0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f2\fs32  current as a stream of charge that flows from a more positively charged area to a more negatively charged area (less positive). That is, the direction of current is defined exactly opposite to the electron flow. This convention was adopted because it is easier to think of a flow going from a higher level (more positive) to a lower level (less positive), like water flowing down hill. \
This definition of current, sometimes called 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\b\fs32 conventional current
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\fs32  for clarity, is the one used by physicists, engineers, and in textbooks.  You should think of current as positive charge flowing from a positive terminal to a negative terminal, even though, in reality, negatively charged electrons flow in the other direction.\
